Osamodas can call on the power of 4 different families of summons based on their needs. Each family is linked to an element and a specialty:
  • Gobballs for protection (Earth element)
  • Tofus for getting around easily (Air element)
  • Wyrmlings for healing (Fire element)
  • Toads for dealing damage (Water element)
<b>Summoning Charges</b> Osamodas earn summoning charges whenever they use their elemental spells, with each element corresponding to a family.
  • Gobbacharge (Earth spells)
  • Tofucharge (Air spells)
  • Wyrmlicharge (Fire spells)
  • Toacharge (Water spells)
You can have up to 4 summoning charges in each element. The first 3 are used to summon a creature from the family, while the last charge triggers the transformation. These charges are displayed in a status bubble above the character. The bubble's colour indicates the element, and its shape shows what creature will be summoned. These bubbles are not visible to the Osamodas's opponents, and the charges cannot be unbewitched. If the summoner uses several spells of the same element, and then a spell of a different element, the summoner doesn't gain another charge but already-earned charges will switch over to the new element. Each family consists of 3 summons with different colours: melanic, albino and colourful. Only one of each summons can exist per summoner in a single fight. The Osamodas must use their elemental spells to earn summoning charges corresponding to the creature they want to summon. For example, to summon an Albino Toad, they must use 2 Water spells in a row, followed by a summoning spell. <b>Summoning Spells</b> Osamodas can use 1 to 6 summoning spells: First, Second, Third, Fourth, Fifth and Sixth. These spells work in a special way. When cast, the consumed summoning charges determine what creature is summoned by the spell, rather than the spell itself. This creature is linked to the spell that summoned it. When it dies, the spell's recast interval is set to a number of turns corresponding to the creature's type (melanic, albino, or colourful). Recasting the spell doesn't re-summon the creature; it moves the creature to the target cell. <b>Osamodas's Whip and Animal Transformation</b> When the summoner accumulates 4 summoning charges, they undergo a transformation based on the charges' element and consume the charges. Allies near the Osamodas or their summons (no more than 2 cells away) earn the bonus corresponding to the transformation. The transformation and associated bonuses last 2 turns. The effects stack from one transformation to the next (twice in each element) and can't be unbewitched from the Osamodas.
  • Gobball: reduces damage taken
  • Tofu: MP bonus
  • Wyrmling: heals allies (doubled when their HP is low)
  • Toad: damage bonus

Description and Function: Portals are glyph-type items on the ground that are not obstacles. They are placed on free cells that do not have traps on them.



Portals are used to teleport entities that move onto or are positioned on them (allies, enemies, monsters, etc.), and to launch spells through them.



Spells have increased damage and healing when launched through portals. The farther away from each other the portals are, the higher the bonus.



Network and Redirection: Portals are connected to each other, forming a "network". There must be 2 active portals for a network to form.



Spells cast through a portal, as well as push or pull manoeuvres that send an entity into a portal, "project" the spell or entity through the exit portal. This projection functions as a vector, which maintains the distance and direction of the spell casting or movement to determine the destination cell.



An entity or spell that enters the network will go from the "entrance portal" to the nearest portal, and so on without passing through the same portal twice, to arrive at the last portal, the "exit portal".



If several portals are an equal distance apart, timing is prioritised to determine the order in which portals are travelled through by a spell or relocated entity.



Hovering the mouse over the network will offer a preview of how it redirects spells and relocations.



Weapons cannot be used through portals.



Destination Cell: If the destination portal is unavailable (occupied by an entity or an obstacle), the portal cannot be used. A portal cannot be placed on a cell already containing a portal.



Line-of-sight restrictions still apply to spells even if they are cast through a network and the theoretical destination cell is located behind an obstacle.



Depending on how an entity or spell enters the network, the destination cell differs:

  • Via walking: the entity arrives at the cell where the destination portal is located.
  • Via (spell) casting: the entity arrives at the cell using the vector between the caster's position and the entrance portal.
  • Via teleportation: the entity arrives at the cell using the vector between the caster's position and the entrance portal.
  • By being pushed: the entity arrives at the cell where the destination portal is located. If the push manoeuvre is interrupted by the entrance portal, the "missing" push is applied from the destination cell (using the push vector).
  • By being pulled: the entity arrives at the cell where the destination portal is located. If the pull manoeuvre is interrupted by the entrance portal, the "missing" pull is applied from the destination cell (using the pull vector).
    • Portals and Teams: Portals take the colour of their team (red or blue). A team is limited to 4 portals, even if there are several Eliotropes on the team.



    The networks of two enemy Eliotropes will not communicate with each other. However, all portals can be used by either allies or enemies.



    Enemies (not including summons) are unable to pass through an enemy portal on the first turn of the game.



    When an Eliotrope dies, their portals disappear.



    Activation: When a portal is placed, it is open by default and therefore part of a network.



    Portals can be closed using the Neutral and Interruption spells. A closed portal is no longer part of the network of portals until the start of the Eliotrope's next turn.



    The Neutral spell is not cast through the network; it directly closes the targeted portal.



    On the contrary, the Portal spell can be cast through a network.



    Standing on a deactivated portal that becomes active again will not teleport the entity.



    Casting a spell through a portal network doesn't deactivate the portals. A character may therefore cast spells through it as many times as they want during their turn.



    However, if an entity walks into or is moved into the network, the entrance and exit portals will be inactive for the entity's current turn, to be reactivated at the start of the next active entity's turn. Order: Portals are numbered from 1 to 4. The first portal placed is number 1, and the following portals go up to 4.



    When an Eliotrope or their team can't set down any more portals, placing another portal will replace the oldest one.



    The new portal then becomes number 4, number 2 becomes 1, and so on.



    Hovering the mouse over a portal will show the order of portals.

Masqueraider gameplay is based on using various different masks, each with distinct abilities.



When a mask is active, it unlocks certain spells while preventing access to others. Some spells can, however, be cast regardless of which mask is active.



Masqueraiders can only use one mask at a time, so they must pace their use depending on their needs.



Each mask applies bonuses on the caster and allies adjacent to the caster when the mask is changed. The bonuses applied to allies only last 2 turns and can be removed via unbewitchment.



The effects of a mask on the caster are infinite as long as they don't change masks and cannot be removed via unbewitchment.



It is possible to change masks 2 times in the same turn. Using a new mask removes all the effects of the previously used mask and sets its recast interval to 1 turn.

Huppermages' elemental spells apply elemental states when they hit an enemy. For example, a spell that deals Fire damage will apply the Fire elemental state to the target.



Each state is represented by a different symbol and colour, which appear above the affected targets and are only visible to the caster.



There are 4 of these states, one for each element. They cannot be removed through unbewitchment, and will remain on targets indefinitely.



Many utility spells will consume targets' elemental states to apply a different effect depending on the state.



<b>Runes</b> Runes are glyph-type items on the ground that are not obstacles. They are placed on cells without traps on them.

When an elemental state is applied to an enemy target, the caster also places a rune under the target. This rune corresponds to the elemental state that was just applied to the target.



There can only be one rune on a cell at a time. If 2 different elemental spells are cast on the same cell, the first rune will be replaced by the second.



Runes last for 2 turns; if not triggered during that period, they disappear without applying any effects.



Runes can be triggered by certain Huppermage spells, and they apply different effects depending on which spell activates it and the rune's element.



They can also be consumed by other spells, for example to increase the spell's damage or another's healing.

<b>Elemental Combinations</b> An elemental combination is generated when 2 different elemental states are applied to the same target. It doesn't matter what order the states are applied in.



When a Huppermage generates an elemental combination, they gain a Power bonus for 2 turns, up to once for every different elemental combination. Depending on the elemental state applied, the target suffers the following effects for 1 turn:

  • Water/Fire combination: Dodge penalty
  • Water/Air combination: final damage dealt penalty
  • Water/Earth combination: MP penalty
  • Earth/Fire combination: final damage received bonus
  • Earth/Air combination: Range steal
  • Air/Fire combination: AP penalty
    • Penalties applied by combinations can be removed through unbewitchment, but the caster's Power bonus cannot be unbewitched.

Sadida gameplay is centred around summoning Trees. When summoned, Trees are in the Puny state, and become Leafy at the start of the caster's next turn.

When the Tree becomes Leafy, it can no longer be pushed or pulled. 15% of the damage suffered in close combat by a Leafy Tree is also applied to all of the other allied Leafy Trees; this is the Intertwined Forest.

A Leafy Tree can be targeted by certain Sadida spells, for example to replace it with another summons or to trigger effects in an area of effect.



Trees are not counted in the caster's maximum number of summons.



<b>Dolls</b> Sadidas are able to summon Dolls, which can reduce AP or MP, lock, heal or deal damage, depending on the Doll. There are two ways to summon a Doll:

  • From an allied Leafy Tree present on the field. Dolls summoned from a Leafy Tree will revert to Puny Trees when they die. However, this new Tree's maximum Vitality will be reduced by 50%.
  • Directly on an empty cell. Dolls summoned on empty cells do not turn into Trees when they die.




    • <b>Infected State</b> Sadidas can apply the Infected state directly using some of their spells, or indirectly through their Dolls or Trees.

    When one of the Sadida's single-target spells hits an enemy in the Infected state, all enemies with the Infected state are also affected by the spell.

    Damage spread to secondary enemies in the Infected state is always the normal damage of the spell used. It can only spread a maximum of 3 times per player turn.



    The state is symbolised by a white bramble on a green background that appears below the characters, and that is visible to all the Sadidas on a team.



    <b>AP Reduction</b> Sadidas can use some of their spells to remove dodgeable Action Points.

    The removed Action Points cannot be regained through unbewitchment.

    <b>MP Reduction</b> Sadidas can use some of their spells to remove dodgeable Movement Points.

    The removed Movement Points cannot be regained through unbewitchment.

Srams can use Invisibility to be invisible to their enemies while remaining visible to their allies.

However, enemies will be able to see a Sram's position if they use a spell, along with any cells on which a trap is triggered.

Inflicting direct damage will instantly remove the invisibility. However, Srams remain invisible after causing trap, poison or pushback damage.

Certain monster classes in the game have spells to reveal invisible entities. It is also possible to reduce or completely remove invisibility by unbewitching the invisible character.

When Srams lose their invisibility¬†‚Äì either because the bonus has expired, an enemy has detected them, or they reveal themselves¬†‚Äì they gain a final damage bonus for 1 turn. This bonus is removed after the first direct damage they inflict during the turn.

<b>Traps</b> Srams are able to set traps on the battlefield, exclusively on free cells. Traps can also be placed on a cell occupied by an Eliotrope Portal, but only if the portal is closed.

Traps are triggered when an entity walks over them or is summoned inside them.

Some traps have a placement zone that differs from its activation zone. For example, the Mass Trap occupies a single cell, but when an entity activates it, its effects are applied to all entities within a 2-cell radius around the placement cell.

These single-cell traps with an area of effect can be triggered by the caster or their allies without affecting them. They will only be affected if they are inside the trap's area of effect, but not if they trigger it.

<b>Trap Arrays</b> By combining their various traps, Srams can create trap arrays, which are chains of several traps, to finish off an opponent.

The traps' effects are triggered in the order in which the traps were set.

Positioning traps can therefore be used to link several damage traps. Pushing or pulling an enemy into the first trap in the array will then successively trigger the rest of the traps if they've been placed correctly.

<b>The Double & the Plotter</b> The Double spell and its Plotter variant both summon a double of the caster with all the same characteristics: Health Points, Dodge, Lock, Resistances, etc.

The Double and the Plotter cannot cast any spells; they can only move around.

Some of the Sram's spells can be used to interact directly or indirectly with a double. The Sram can also use them to activate traps from a distance.

Rogues can summon Bombs to the field on any unoccupied cell. Bombs are "inert" summons, meaning they don't use spells or move around.



A Rogue can have up to 3 Bombs on the battlefield simultaneously, in the same element or not. Bombs are not counted in the caster's maximum number of summons. Their Health Points depend on the caster's level.



When a Bomb is summoned, it increases the AP cost of the spell that summoned it by 1 while it is alive. However, their variants, the Resilient Bombs, have a fixed AP cost.



A Bomb can also be cast on an occupied cell. In this case, it explodes automatically and inflicts damage in its element on the target and surrounding entities in a radius of 2 cells. If the target is another of the caster's Bombs, it gains 1 Combo before exploding.



There is a different type of Bomb for every element:

  • Explobombs inflict Fire damage. Its damage is greater than the others when it forms a wall.
  • Grenados inflict Air damage. They remove MP.
  • Water Bombs inflict Water damage. They remove AP.
  • Seismobombs inflict Earth damage. Its damage is greater than the others when it explodes.


    • Several spells can be used to detonate a Bomb from a distance, either to simply deal damage or to be able to set another Bomb elsewhere on the battlefield.



    If a Bomb is killed by some means other than a spell causing it to detonate, it will die normally without causing any damage or reductions.



    <b>Combos & Explosions</b> At the start of each turn, Rogues will give 2 Combos to each of their Bombs present on the field. Combos increase from 1 to a maximum of 15, and the status icon above each Bomb indicates its Combo level.

    The Combo increases the size of the Bombs and especially the damage they inflict via walls and explosions.



    When a Bomb is summoned, it appears in Combo I.

    Combo Bonuses:

  • - I: 0% - II: 20% - III: 40% - IV: 60% - V: 80% - VI: 100% - VII: 120% - VIII: 140% - IX: 160% - X: 190% - XI: 220% - XII: 250% - XIII: 280% - XIV: 320% - XV: 360%




    When a Bomb explodes, if the caster's other Bombs are in the blast zone, they explode as well. Each Bomb's combo bonus is applied to the other Bombs in the zone, significantly increasing the damage done by each Bomb.

    <b>Bomb Walls</b> When at least 2 Bombs are in a line and 2 to 6 spaces apart, they automatically form a Bomb "wall". This appears as a glyph on the ground, which doesn't impede movement or line of sight. A wall can therefore be made of up to 3 bombs maximum.

    Any entity that moves across or steps on the wall will take damage; the same applies to starting a turn inside the wall.



    Moving an entity into a wall will halt its movement and do damage to it. If this entity has already suffered the wall's effects during the turn, it will not be impeded and will not take damage if placed inside it again.

    However, walking in the wall doesn't have this same once-per-turn limit; it will therefore inflict damage for every MP spent by the entity in the wall.



    If one Bomb is linked to others by a wall and it explodes, it will detonate the other Bombs in the wall.



    Air walls, i.e. those formed by Grenados, reduce targets' MP immediately and at the start of the turn. This is also true for Water walls, but they reduce AP.



    Walls take advantage of half of the Combo to inflict their damage. Wall damage is also greatly reduced outside of the Rogue's and its summons' turns.

    <b>Kaboom</b> The Kaboom and Imposture spells apply the Kaboom state on the caster and their allies, protecting them from damage caused by explosions and walls. The penalties applied by bomb explosions become bonuses that last for 3 turns; each can stack 2 times for a total of 3 bonuses maximum:

  • Explobomb: 2 Range




  • Grenado: 1 MP




  • Water Bomb: 1 AP




  • Seismobomb: 5% Final Damage

    The removed Action Points cannot be regained through unbewitchment.

    Rogues can use some of their spells to remove parryable Movement Points.

    The removed Movement Points cannot be regained through unbewitchment.

Introduction Turrets are crucial to Foggernaut gameplay. There are 6 turrets, and each performs very different roles depending on the summoner's needs.



  • Harpooner and Drill (Damage, Unbewitchment and Erosion)
  • Lifesaver and Bathyscaphe (Healing, Protection and Enhancement)
  • Tacturret and Trawler (Positioning and Interference)




    • Each turret has an active spell it uses on its turn, which affects both allies and enemies. Upgrading Turrets The unique feature of these summons is that they can be improved; the Foggernaut can use the Evolution and Transition spells to upgrade turrets. Upgrading a turret heals it by 100% of its HP.



    They're at Evolution I by default, and they go up to Evolution II, then III. After reaching Evolution III, the turret unlocks its special spell.



    One turret can be improved per turn, and only one turret can be at Evolution III at one time. If one already has a turret at Evolution III and upgrades a second turret from Evolution II to III, the first turret will revert to level II.



    Evolution III also makes it so offensive turrets no longer have to attack allies, and defensive turrets no longer have to heal or block enemies. Evolution Bonuses Evolution levels II and III also allow turrets to grant bonuses to their summoner. Each turret gives different bonuses to its summoner; the bonuses are higher at Evolution III than at II and can only be dissipated with the death of the turret. These bonuses apply for 1 turn if the Foggernaut is no more than 7 cells away and in the turret's line of sight.

Pandawas can use their spells to alternate between 2 states: Sober and Drunk.

The Drunk state lowers Pandawas' mobility by removing an MP but it allows them to better withstand damage received. This mode is made for close combat.

The Sober state, on the other hand, is based on positioning and ranged gameplay.

Most spells have different effects based on the Pandawas' state.

Some spells have identical effects regardless of the state, while yet others can only be cast in one state or the other.

When in the Drunk state, Pandawas cannot carry allies or enemies and cannot use their weapons.

<b>Carrying and Throwing</b> Pandawas have the unique ability to carry and throw their allies and enemies.

Every time they carry an entity, they gain Power. This bonus evolves with each Pandawa's level.

A target can only be carried in close combat but can then be thrown some distance away.

Pandawas have different ways to throw entities, for example, drawing toward the destination cell, or healing the entity thrown.

When a Pandawa carries an entity, they can no longer cast their spells, except for those allowing them to throw the entity.

An entity being carried by a Pandawa can't be targeted by "direct" spells; the Pandawa will suffer the effects, including damage.

If the entity is an ally, it cannot inflict damage while it is being carried.

If a Pandawa is carrying one of their Barrels or Bamboos, they immediately regain 1 AP.
